post_text:
Kearney Public Schools has received a waiver from the USDA to provide meals free of charge to all students beginning Wednesday, September 16 through December 22, or until the funds run out.

Students must choose a complete meal containing at least three items, and one must be a fruit or vegetable to qualify for the free meal. Extra food items like second entrees, additional milk, or any other ala carte items are not included in the waiver. Students will need to have money in their Bearcat Diner account or pay cash for extra items. This waiver is only for student meals. Meal prices will return to normal status in January.

Menus will be subject to change due to product availability.

Photo: Emmett from Meadowlark

post_text: The Kearney High School Athletic and Media Productions departments are proud to announce their continuing partnership with Striv, a Nebraska-based company, to stream live events to Bearcat Nation. In light of current events, a pay per view charge will be assessed for each game. $10 for football and $5 for other Fall sports. Directions for the PPV will be displayed on the Kearney High Striv homepage, (striv.tv/channel/kearney). These proceeds will help offset lost revenue. We thank you all for your understanding and continue support of the Bearcat Sports Network. If you have any questions, please contact KHS Asst Principal/Activities Director Ryan Hogue.

Park Elementary
August 26 at 10:21 AM ¬∑

Daniel Falk presented a Gaga Pit to Park Elementary as part of his Eagle Scout requirements. The pit was designed by Daniel and constructed with the help of other KHS students, many of whom attended Park Elementary. Unique to this Gaga Ball pit, Daniel added wheels so the pit can be easily moved inside or to another location. In addition, the pit can be divided into two pits for additional play.

Thank you to Daniel, the sponsors/donors, and construction helpers for this great addition to Park Elementary School.

Gaga Ball is played like dodge ball only with one ball. When the ball hits you below your knees, you are out of the game.

If you are interested in the Boy Scouts of America, The Overland Trails Council is holding a Family Outing on Tuesday, August 25 at Harmon Park at 6:30 pm. There will be scavenger hunts, smores, tomahawks and more.

KHS Senior, Matthew Dahlke, has been selected to the National Association for Music Education (NAfME) National Honors Orchestra. Each year, students across the country send in a rigorous audition video, and Dahlke was selected on the viola for 2020. On average, less than 15 violas are chosen from the entire country, so he is considered one of the BEST viola players in the country.
‚ÄúThis is a huge honor, a huge accomplishment for Matt,‚Äù states Pat Nebesniak, KHS Orchestra teacher. ‚ÄúThis is about the biggest accomplishment a high school musician can achieve.‚Äù
Mathew‚Äôs parents are Todd and Teresa Dahlke.

Two Rivers Public Health
Announces Updated Testing Schedule

KEARNEY ‚ÄìTwo Rivers Public Health Department has worked with Test Nebraska to get COVID-19 testing sites set up in every county in the district, and are pleased to release the updated schedule for testing. Sites are available every weekday in at least one location throughout the service area. Anyone wishing to get a test can register and get tested. It is a free test supported by the State of Nebraska. Two Rivers highly recommends those who are experiencing symptoms be tested, but Test Nebraska will also accept children and adults who have no symptoms. Tests through TestNebraska are free.

Kaitlin Berck of Kearney High School is one of 15 students selected as a member of Congressman Smith‚Äôs 2020-2021 Youth Advisory Council

Smith‚Äôs Youth Advisory Council is a forum for high school students to discuss opinions, thoughts, and concerns about local and federal issues with Smith throughout the school year. Through in-person meetings and other forums, the council provides students an opportunity for involvement and insight into their government and communities.

The council is open to junior and senior high school students who are selected through an application process in the spring. More information is available on Smith‚Äôs website at AdrianSmith.house.gov/YouthAdvisoryCouncil.

Kearney Businesses,

As a result of the recent pandemic caused by COVID-19 in Buffalo County, Nebraska, and across the globe, a group of Buffalo County entities has collaborated to form the Buffalo County Joint Information Center. The purpose of the JIC is to ensure that residents of Buffalo County have as much accurate and complete information regarding the event as possible.

One of the first acts this collaboration has determined is essential is hosting a Q&A session for businesses regarding safety of their staff and patrons during this event, with cooperation from Buffalo County Community Partners. A live session will be hosted online Tuesday, August 18, 2020, at 10 am Central Time. It will be live-streamed on the Two Rivers Facebook page. CLICK THE LINK TO VIEW THIS SESSION. Questions will be presented through the comment section and answered as time allows. The session will also be recorded, so those who are unable to attend can view a recording at their convenience.

https://www.facebook.com/events/231823714741597/

KEARNEY, Neb. ‚Äî Community members can get medication lock boxes and gunlocks free of charge thanks to funding from the Nebraska State Suicide Prevention Coalition and donations from the Nebraska Veteran‚Äôs Affairs.

According to the Buffalo County Community Partners (BCCP), the lockboxes and gunlocks are available by calling Richard Young Hospital at 308-865-2000.

These are available through a partnership between the Buffalo County Community Partners‚Äô Suicide Prevention Coalition, Opioid Taskforce, Nebraska Veteran‚Äôs Affairs, and Richard Young Hospital.

BCCP said reducing access to prescriptions and firearms will help to saves lives.

The lockboxes and gunlocks will come with instructions. The lockboxes will also include crisis response numbers.

post_text:
FREE ACT FOR CLASS OF 2021

The Nebraska Department of Education and ACT have teamed up to offer a Free make-up college-entrance exam to Nebraska seniors, who lost their testing opportunity due to the extended closure for Covid-19. Principal Loofe sent e-mails to all seniors and parents/guardians explaining the option to test. It is not a mandatory test.

Any student in the Class of 2021 wanting to take the free September 22 make-up ACT because you need a college-entrance exam score, e-mail kmadsen@kearneycats.com to get on the test roster.

Currently, 150 seniors are registered, but only about 40% of those eligible to register have done so. Historically 70% of a KHS class takes the ACT. Friday, July 24 is the deadline to register so time is running out.

Get on your e-mail and send a message to assistant principal Madsen. If a senior qualified for a testing accommodation last spring, that will also be available September 22. Friday is the deadline!

Students from Kearney High School and KCHS help the Community Action Partnership Food Bank.

The Food Bank receives over 1000 boxes of 'Farm to Table' program food from the USDA because of the pandemic every Thursday.

They have been rolling out approximately 1000 boxes of food every week to families in need in Buffalo County.

If you can volunteer on Thursday mornings to move boxes of food into trailers for delivery to our hungry neighbors, contact (308) 865-5683.

Get a tour of the food bank. The work they are doing will touch your heart.

post_text: The Kearney Public Schools Foundation has realized that students and families in our district are going through a difficult time. Due to this, the KPS Foundation has launched a new fund to help those in our school district who are in need. Support the Kearney Public School District students and families by donating through the COVID-19 Assistance Fund. Your gift will help provide basic needs through the Kearney Public Schools Social Workers. Give online at https://kps.z2systems.com/np/clients/kps/donation.jsp?campaign=204&&test=true or mail your gift to: COVID 19 Assistance Fund, Kearney Public Schools Foundation, 320 West 24th Avenue.

Community Action Partnership of Mid-Nebraska
Provides emergency rental and utility assistance, commodity supplement food packages to seniors, mobile produce distribution from Food Bank, community health worker outreach to minority populations, remote outreach to our Early Head Start and Head Start families, provides healthy foods at no cost, nutrition information, connections to community services and breastfeeding support to women, infants and children through the WIC program and public transportation with RYDE Transit. Call (308) 865-5675 for more information or check out the website (http://communityactionmidne.com/) or agency Facebook page (http://communityactionmidne.com)

NOTICE - SPORTS PHYSICALS FOR 20-21
DUE TO THE CORONAVIRUS:

Sports physical on file for 2019-2020 school year for any current 9-11 grade students will now also be valid for the 2020-2021 school year. All incoming freshmen (Current 8th graders) will still be required to provide sports physical paperwork that is dated no earlier than May 1, 2020.

The physicals that the current 7th graders have on file for the 2019-2020 school year can be used for NSAA/athletic purposes for the 2020-2021 school year.

post_text:
Congratulation to Robin Bennett, Meadowlark Elementary Teacher! Robin was selected at NTV Teacher of the Month. Eight of her students nominated Mrs. Bennett for the award.
She was surprised in a Zoom meeting with the staff, students, and Kent Boughten! Watch NTV tonight!

Mrs. Bennett commented:
"I am so blessed to work with the staff and students of Meadowlark. My kids have truly made my heart happy again. Every day we try to find joy in the world and I am so grateful for my kids. Be the light for others. I miss my kids so much and try to find ways to connect with them through this situation. Thank you so much. I feel so blessed. These kids have made such a difference in my life. My heart is so full. Stay safe and healthy. Wash your hands."

Kearney Public Schools Foundation is happy to recognize a few special people who stand out in an already exceptional crowd! Along with Kearney Public Schools and First National Bank, please help us congratulate the following:

Teresa Cordes of Central Elementary and Julie Everett of Meadowlark Elementary have been chosen as the 2020 Outstanding Educators for Kearney Public Schools.

Nikki Peterson, Kearney High School Social Worker was chosen as the 2020 Outstanding Support Staff.

Cynthia (CJ) Sabah was chosen as the 2020 Outstanding Retired Educator.

Stacy Schulte was chosen as the 2020 recipient of the Outstanding Volunteer Award for her dedication to Emerson Elementary.

The 2020 Distinguished Graduate is Tom Tye II of Kearney & KHS Class of 1978.

We look forward to rescheduling a date for the Celebration of Excellence to honor this year‚Äôs award recipients.

Parents are asked to visit kearneyregional.com/doctors-day-coloring
to download a coloring page for their child(ren) to color. They can then upload it back on the same website. All submissions will then be printed off and hung around the campus on Doctors' Day, Monday, March 30th.

Community members can also leave well wishes on the website that will also be shared.

All coloring pages and messages should be uploaded by midnight on Saturday, March 28th.

post_text:
KPS Families,

With the United States expansion of the travel ban, and the desire to flatten the COVID-19 curve and not overwhelm our medical community, Kearney Public Schools, along with Hastings and Grand Island Public Schools, will be extending students‚Äô Spring Break starting tomorrow, March 16 through March 29.

There has not been a confirmed case in Buffalo, Hall, or Adams County, however, CDC guidance requires social distancing and separation of large groups of people. We view our regular school day as something that would constitute a large gathering. We also see this extended break as an opportunity to thoroughly clean and disinfect our buildings and our facilities team will work diligently to make sure we have cleaned all areas appropriately. Additionally, all activities and sports practices will be cancelled and KCLC will not be in session.

Our top priority is the safety of our students, staff and, in this case, the greater community and we hope these efforts will serve our community health in a productive way.

We also see this extended break as an opportunity to thoroughly clean and disinfect our buildings and our facilities team will work diligently to make sure we have cleaned all areas appropriately. post_text:
Two Kearney High School students were selected to display their work in the 23rd Annual National K-12 Ceramic Exhibition in Richmond, Virginia. Over 939 pieces of art from students K-12 across the United States were entered into the exhibition. Only 150 were selected to be included in the exhibition. From the 723 entries competing at the 11th-12th grade level, two of the selected entries were Nature's Dominance, created by Brooklyn Liljehorn and Sight, created by Leah Glendenning, both students are 11th graders at KHS. These students created the artwork in ceramics classes at Kearney High School under the direction of art instructor Katrina (McCarter) Olmstead. This year's work was selected by the esteemed juror Keith Williams, of Concordia University. Williams, artist and educator since the late 1970s, is the Chairperson of the Department of Art and Professor of Art and Art History.

Blue: Nature's Dominance by Brooklyn Liljehorn
Floral: Sight by Leah Glendenning

Bright Futures Toddler Program celebrates earning a Step Up to Quality - Step 5 Rating

Kearney, Nebraska ‚Äì Quality child care and early childhood education is important in our state‚Äôs future. Step Up to Quality is celebrating its fifth anniversary in 2019, assisting programs like the KPS Bright Futures Toddler Program to go beyond state licensing requirements to better serve the needs of young children and their families and to prepare them for success in kindergarten and beyond. The KPS Bright Futures Toddler Program has been a part of Step Up to Quality since its inception and has earned the highest ranking possible, a Step 5.

If you haven't received an invitation in the past and would like one to be mailed to you, please call or email Pam Hill, Class Act Director, at classact@kearneycats.com or 308 698-8048; however, you do not need an invitation to attend.

This year's Raffle is to Napa Valley, California: 3 nights accommodations for two at a beautifully restored 1901 farmhouse. This includes wine tours & tasting, cave tours and tasting, 150 gift certificate to the Culinary Arts Institute of America, which can be used for dinner or cooking classes, and so much more.

If you would like more information on the 15th Annual Class Act Event or the Raffle, please let us know.

Class Act does wonderful things for Kearney Public Schools and its students with the money it raises through this event. Please consider attending and helping us make this year our best event ever!

Watch for more information on Class Act 15!

KPS Board of Education member, Kathy Gifford, helps TeamMates wrap gifts at the Hilltop Mall on Wednesday night.

TeamMate Mentors and Mentees will be staffing the booth evenings and weekends from December 6 through Christmas Eve.

Busy shoppers are invited to bring gifts they purchased at the Mall, ordered online or purchased at other retail stores to be wrapped.

Proceeds help support the activities of the Kearney TeamMate Program. TeamMate Mentees wrapping gifts are helping support a program they benefit from. They are also building social skills, problem-solving and critical thinking skills.

The TeamMates Mentoring Program was founded in 1991 by Tom and Nancy Osborne to provide support and encouragement to school-aged youth. TeamMates of Kearney Public Schools have been serving youth since 1999 and currently serve 67 youth. Mentors meet one hour per week at the school to provide support and encouragement to youth. To become a mentor go to www.teammates.org.

The Eaton Star Student for December is Ryder Melton, 5th grader at Park Elementary.

Ryder was nominated by his teacher, Jenae Loeffelholz, for being compassionate, kind, and hard-working. She says that she most admires his kind heart and love for his family (especially his older brother), and wants Ryder to know how incredible he really is. Congratulations, Ryder!

Photo from left: Park Elementary Principal Chance Waggoner, Emily Stiles from Eaton, 5th-grade teacher Jenae Loeffelholz, mother Lori Melton, winner Ryder Melton, grandparents Dan and Nelta Melton, and Lynelle ‚ÄúPokey‚Äù Oliver from Eaton.

The Kearney High School Clothing Class did a collaborative project with Barb Thompson's 1st-grade students at Kenwood Elementary.
The 1st-graders were provided with "Ugly Doll" patterns to color and personalize. The Clothing students took the colored patterns and turned them into dolls through the magic of hand and machine sewing!

The Kearney High students personally delivered the "Ugly Dolls" to the students at Kenwood.

Read about it on the Kearney Hub!

post_text:
SKATE for the MDA

Tickets & merchandise are now available for the annual UNK SIGEP Skate-a-thon, October 27. KHS DECA is helping fundraise for the Muscular Dystrophy Association (MDA).

Visit our page (https://unk.crowdchange.co/9140/page/142337) to make purchases and/or donations. ALL proceeds go directly to the Muscular Dystrophy Association (MDA).

At this fundraiser, ticket holders can ice skate & visit the carnival from 6-9 pm!

Please help send a child with Muscular Dystrophy to MDA summer camp where their condition does not limit their ability to participate in activities.
